{{Infobox language |name=Italian Sign Language |nativename=''Lingua dei Segni Italiana'' |region=[[Italy]], [[San Marino]], [[Switzerland]]<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Pizzuto | first1 = Elena | last2 = Corazza | first2 = Serena | year = 1996 | title = Noun morphology in Italian Sign Language (LIS) | url = | journal = Lingua | volume = 98 | issue = 1–3| pages = 169–196 | doi = 10.1016/0024-3841(95)00037-2 }}</ref> |speakers=40,000 |date=2013<!--not in archived 2012 version of page--> |ref=<ref>[http://www.eud.eu/Italy-i-187.html EUD: Italy] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720161121/http://www.eud.eu/Italy-i-187.html |date=2011-07-20 }}</ref> |familycolor=Sign |fam1=[[French Sign Language family|French sign]] |iso3=ise |lc1=slf|ld1=Swiss-Italian SL |glotto=ital1288 |glottorefname=Italian Sign }}
'''Italian Sign Language''' or '''LIS''' (''Lingua dei Segni Italiana'') is the [[sign language|visual language]] used by [[deaf]] people in [[Italy]]. Deep analysis of it began in the 1980s, along the lines of [[William Stokoe]]'s research on [[American Sign Language]] in the 1960s. Until the beginning of the 21st century, most studies of Italian Sign Language dealt with its phonology and vocabulary. According to the European Union for the Deaf, the majority of the 60,000–90,000 Deaf people in Italy use LIS.
==Structure== Like many sign languages, LIS is in some ways different from its "spoken neighbour"; thus, it has little in common with spoken [[Italian language|Italian]], but shares some features with non-[[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]] oral languages (e.g. it is verb final, like the [[Basque language]]; it has inclusive and exclusive pronominal forms like oceanic languages; interrogative particles are verb final (''You go where?'').
A sign variety of spoken Italian also exists, the so-called [[Manually Coded Language|Signed Italian]] which combines LIS lexicon with the grammar of spoken Italian: this is not Italian Sign Language, however.
Some features of LIS are typical of sign languages in general, e.g. agreement between nouns, adjectives and verbs is not based on gender (masculine, feminine, neuter) but it is based on place, that is the spatial position in which the sign is performed: nouns can be placed everywhere in the space but their position must be consistent with that of pronouns and verbs. The LIS translation of the sentence "The child speaks to the mother" appears as ''Child-here mother-there this-speak-that'', rather than involving forms like "he, she". The voice intonation is replaced by facial expressions which mark interrogative sentences, imperatives and relative clauses. Other features of Italian Sign Language which can be found also in oral languages are: classifiers; dual, trial, quattrial and even quinquial forms in addition to the general plural; verbs inflected for person.
